The patient has lymphocytosis, mild lymphadenopathy, and flow cytometry showing CD5, 19, 20, 23 positive population, which are all suggestive of chronic lymphocytic leukemia. The patient’s past medical history of hypertension and hyperlipidemia, as well as current medications, are not contributing factors to the diagnosis of leukemia. The other options, tuberculosis, acute lymphoblastic leukemia, and immune thrombocytopenic purpura, are not consistent with the given symptoms and laboratory results.
